      "content": "Absolutely, a child with a fever can be given a dose of aspirin, but only if it's not too high of a fever. A 200-300 mg dose every 4-6 hours should help bring the fever down. Make sure to use the lowest dose possible, and no more than five doses in 24 hours. Remember, if the fever doesn't start to decrease, it's time to call a doctor. Also, aspirin should not be given to children with a fever due to the risk of Reye's syndrome. Be sure to use acetaminophen instead.",
